03916nam a22006855i 9780292799165DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927991657 a10.7560/7312262doi  a(DE-B1597)588005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPR6015.U9bN68 2000eb 7aDRA0030002bisacsh04a822/.9122221 aHuxley, Aldous, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNow More Than Ever /cAldous Huxley; ed. by James Sexton, David Bradshaw. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA Note on the Text -- tNow More Than Ever -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of his career, British writer Aldous Huxley (1894-1963) shifted away from elitist social satires and an atheistic outlook toward greater concern for the masses and the use of religious terms and imagery. This change in Huxley's thinking underlies the previously unpublished play Now More Than Ever. Written in 1932-1933 just after Brave New World, Now More Than Ever is a response to the social, economic, and political upheavals of its time. Huxley's protagonist is an idealistic financier whose grandiose schemes for controlling the means of production drive him to swindling and finally to suicide. His fate allows Huxley to expose the evils he perceives in free-market capitalism while pleading the case for national economic planning and the rationalization of Britain's industrial base. This volume contains the full text of Now More Than Ever, which was believed to be lost until 1976, when a copy was found at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center of the University of Texas at Austin. A "thinker's play" that has never been produced on stage, it is the last previously unpublished piece of Huxley's major writings and immensely important to understanding his development as a writer. The editors of this volume have annotated the play for contemporary readers. Their introduction sets the play in the context of Huxley's intellectual life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCapitalists and financiersvDrama. 0aCommunistsvDrama. 0aFathers and daughtersvDrama. 7aDRAMA / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aBradshaw, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBradshaw, David.1 aHuxley, Aldous, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSexton, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSexton, James.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799165/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK